Saône, Franche-Comté, France":"Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France","Montigny-lès-Cherlieu, Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France":"Montigny-lès-Cherlieu, Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Henri","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Henry</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henri de Fouvent was born in 1165, in France, his father, Humbert IV de Fouvent, was 16 and his mother, Clémence de Montigny, was 16. He married Agnès De Neufchâteau about 1179. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1228, in Montigny-lès-Cherlieu, Haute-Saône, Franche-Comté, France, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1165–1228":"1165–1228","1160–1221